{{Infobox court case | name = Hamilton v Papakura District Council (New Zealand) | court = [[Judicial Committee of the Privy Council]] | date_filed = | image = Coat of arms of New Zealand.svg | date decided = 28 February 2002 | full name = Hamilton & Anor v. Papakura District Council & Watercare Services Limited | citations = [2000] 1 NZLR 265, [2002] 3 NZLR 308, [2002] UKPC 9 | judges = [[Lord Nicholls of Birkenhead]], [[Brian Hutton, Baron Hutton|Lord Hutton]], [[Lord Rodger of Earlsferry]], [[Andrew Leggatt|Sir Andrew Leggatt]], [[Kenneth Keith|Sir Kenneth Keith]] | prior actions = | subsequent actions = | opinions = | transcripts = [http://www.bailii.org/cgi-bin/markup.cgi?doc=/uk/cases/UKPC/2002/9.html Privy Council judgment] | Keywords = negligence }} '''Hamilton v Papakura District Council''' (New Zealand) [2002] UKPC 9 is a cited case in New Zealand regarding liabililty under tort for negligence under [[Rylands v Fletcher]].<ref name="McLay">{{cite book |title=Butterworths Student Companion Torts |edition=4th |last1=McLay |first1=Geoff |publisher=LexisNexis |ISBN=0-408-71686-X|year=2003 |page=}}</ref>
==Background== The Hamiltons grew [[hydroponic]] [[cherry tomato]]es, using the [[Papakura]] town water supply to supply their water needs. When they found their crop had been destroyed, they claimed that the water supply company and the local council were at fault, claiming that the water was contaminated by minute traces of herbicide in the water supply.
They claimed that this was a breach of the [[Sale of Goods Act]] [1908].
