{{Infobox SCC |case-name=Kindler v Canada (Minister of Justice) |full-case-name=Joseph John Kindler v Mr John Crosbie, Minister of Justice and Attorney General of Canada |heard-date=21 February 1991 |decided-date=26 September 1991 |citations=[1991] 2 SCR 779 |docket=21321 |history=APPEAL from ''Kindler v Canada (Minister of Justice'', [1989] 2 FCR 492 ([[Federal Court of Appeal|FCA]]) |subsequent= |ruling=Appeal dismissed |ratio= |SCC=1991-1992 |Unanimous= |Majority=La Forest JJ |JoinMajority=L'Heureux-Dubé and Gonthier JJ |Concurrence=McLachlin J |JoinConcurrence= |Concurrence/Dissent= |JoinConcurrence/Dissent= |Dissent=Sopinka J |JoinDissent=Lamer CJ |Dissent2=Cory J |NotParticipating=Stevenson and Iacobucci JJ |LawsApplied= }} '''''Kindler v Canada (Minister of Justice)''''' <ref>[1991] 2 S.C.R. 779 {{Cite CanLII|source=scc|year=1991|num=70}}</ref> was a landmark decision of the [[Supreme Court of Canada]] where it was held that the government policy that allowed for [[extradition]] of convicted criminals to a country where they may face the [[death penalty]] was valid under the [[Canadian Charter of Rights and Freedoms]]. The Court repeated this finding in ''[[Reference re Ng Extradition]]'' in 1991. However, ''Kindler'' was essentially overruled in 2001 with ''[[United States v. Burns]]''.
After being convicted of murder in [[Pennsylvania]], Joseph Kindler escaped and fled to Canada. He was captured, escaped again and was captured again. Kindler then fought his extradition. In a four-to-three decision the Court found that there was no violation of [[Section Seven of the Canadian Charter of Rights and Freedoms|section 7]] of the Charter (the [[right to life]], [[liberty]] and [[security of person]]) or [[Section Twelve of the Canadian Charter of Rights and Freedoms|section 12]] of the Charter (protection against [[cruel and unusual punishment]]). The case cited an earlier extradition decision, ''[[Canada v. Schmidt]]'' (1987), which states extradition may be unconstitutional under section 7 if it "[[shocks the conscience]]." In ''Kindler'', the Court noted that while [[Canada]] itself had abolished the death penalty, Canada should respect that most other countries had not. This included the [[United States]], with which Canada shared cultural connections and an easily crossed border. Thus, extradition with the possibility of execution should not shock the conscience.
Kindler was ultimately returned to the United States. On December 8, 2009, the [[United States Supreme Court]] ruled in ''[[Beard v. Kindler]]'' that Kindler's flight from the United States constituted an abandonment of his right to appeal.<ref>''Beard v. Kindler'', United States Supreme Court No. 08-992 (available at [https://www.supremecourt.gov/opinions/09pdf/08-992.pdf]).</ref>
